{[show S]Opener's rebid is where shape and strength come into focus, describing the hand a second time after partner has answered.
[BID 1D] ⟦You open the bidding with a minimum hand and no five-card major, so you start with your longer minor, 1\D.⟧ Your partner responds 1\H, showing four or more hearts and enough strength to answer at the one level.
[BID 2H] ⟦You hold four-card heart support, so you raise partner's major and the fit is found. Raising only to 2\H, the cheapest level, tells partner this is a minimum opener with nothing extra, roughly 12 to 15. The level is the whole message: a single raise promises support but denies the values that would justify a jump.⟧
[show NESW]South held \SJ942 \HAQ85 \DKQ9 \C64, a flat 12-count. The opening 1\D got things going, and when responder showed hearts, South's four-card support turned the auction into a search for the right level. With a bare minimum the single raise to 2\H said it all: support, but no spare values. The partnership landed in a comfortable partscore, exactly where minimum-opposite-minimum belongs.}
