[BID 1D] ⟦You open 1\D, since with a long diamond suit and opening values the diamonds name themselves.⟧ Your partner responds 1\H, promising four or more hearts and the values to respond.
[BID 2D] ⟦You have only two hearts, so there is no fit to raise and no new suit worth showing; instead you rebid your own long suit. Repeating diamonds at the cheapest level, 2\D, shows six or more diamonds and a minimum opener. A jump to 3\D would invite game, so the quiet 2\D keeps the auction low and honest about your strength.⟧
[show NESW]South held \SQ \HK7 \DAT85432 \CK64, a one-suiter built around seven diamonds and 12 HCP. There was no four-card major to introduce and no support for hearts, so the hand described itself by simply rebidding diamonds. The cheap 2\D marked the minimum; with more, opener would have jumped. Partner now knows the shape and can place the contract.}
