[BID 1D] ⟦You open 1\D, balanced but too weak to open 1\N, so you start with your longer minor.⟧ Your partner responds 1\S, showing four or more spades and the values to answer.
[BID 1N] ⟦You have only three spades, so you cannot raise, and no new suit is worth showing; but a balanced minimum has a perfect call. Rebidding 1\N shows a flat 12 to 14 and describes your strength and shape in one bid. It is the picture bid opener reaches for when there is no fit and nothing else to say.⟧ Your partner now bids 2\H, showing a second suit, five spades and four hearts, and asking you to choose between the majors.
[BID 2S] ⟦With three cards in each major you give preference back to spades, partner's first suit, by bidding 2\S. When you like two suits equally, returning to the one partner named first is the standard choice, and it keeps the partnership in its longer trump fit.⟧
[show NESW]South held \SA85 \H984 \DJ875 \CAK3, a textbook balanced 12-count. Unable to raise spades with only three, opener described everything with the 1\N rebid. When responder showed both majors, South took the 3-3 preference back to spades. A balanced minimum rarely needs more than one notrump to tell its story.}
